This was somewhat disappointing, and it's unclear what exactly caused it. As winter set in on our New England campus, fewer people were likely commuting by bike or walking, which could partially explain the reduction. December is also the conclusion of the fall semester, a time when everyone is preoccupied with completing assignments and grading. It's possible that filling out the commuter logs simply became less of a priority. Furthermore, December is the start of the hectic holiday season, leading into a month-long break when many students and faculty are not required to be on campus. Classes pick back up in late January for the spring semester, which might also contribute to the lower number of logs submitted that month. However, this doesn't fully account for the low submissions in February. Perhaps it's typical for a project like this to start with enthusiasm that gradually wanes. To address this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a campaign aimed at revitalizing interest, which successfully boosted log submissions that month. Thus, one of the obstacles we encountered was sustaining project momentum amidst both a natural dip in engagement and the specific challenges posed by holiday and semester breaks common in academic settings. Another challenge inherent in this project (or any initiative promoting alternative commuting) is that people value the autonomy and convenience of driving their own vehicles, a deeply ingrained cultural preference. Therefore, offering incentives for alternative commuting is crucial. We distributed numerous prizes, including gift certificates to local eateries, coffee shops, massage services, an independent bookstore, and some national retail chains. It would have been intriguing to see how offering more substantial prizes, like a high-quality bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car, might have influenced participation—potentially alleviating the engagement drop we experienced. The prizes remained relatively constant throughout the project. If their value had escalated over time, it might have spurred increased participation. While the gift cards were sufficient at the project's start, announcing more significant prizes like a couple of bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January could have potentially boosted engagement instead of seeing it decline.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I was particularly intrigued by the trick films, totaling fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films cleverly employ editing techniques to create visual illusions. My analysis mainly centered on detailing the stylistic features of most trick films and identifying the unique elements in some of the later ones. Typically, trick films from the turn of the century are confined to set environments, framed within a frontal proscenium, devoid of camera movement, and utilize long and medium shots, strictly adhering to the one shot equals one film principle. Nonetheless, some films from the early 1900s defy these conventions by incorporating multiple shots.

A prominent feature shared by trick films is their use of interior sets framed by a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary, not following the subjects or objects. This setup, prevalent in early cinema, draws inspiration from theatre and, for trick films, from vaudeville and magic shows. A limitation of this stage-based approach is that characters in trick films usually move laterally and seldom approach or retreat from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move horizontally. Even when they exit the frame, the camera stays put.

The frontal proscenium composition also results in predominantly long shots, with occasional medium shots. Close-ups are absent in any trick films from the Edison library. This approach mirrors theatre and vaudeville traditions, where audiences view the entire performance within the stage's confines. As in most early films, actors remain in the middle ground, precluding close-ups.

Generally, early trick films follow the pattern of one conceptual shot equating to a film, limiting their duration to about a minute or less, based on frames per second. This restricts the trick films' narrative or dramatic potential; they often focus on brief vaudeville-style tricks like magic, disappearing acts, and transformations, with minimal storytelling. However, in trick films, one conceptual shot perceived by the viewer doesn't necessarily correspond to a single physical shot. A single "shot" might comprise several spliced together to create an illusion of appearance or disappearance. In The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), a detailed examination reveals the transition point where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, despite the viewer perceiving the entire film as one continuous shot.

In The Rise of the Gothic Novel, Ian Watt refers to the "Gothic Novel" as an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" highlighting its paradoxical nature. The Gothic style has faced a range of opinions—it's been criticized, celebrated, accused of lacking substance, and applauded for its 'terrible sublime' quality, as Burke notes. Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, the first "Gothic Novel," blended elements from both "ancient and modern" romances, establishing what would become the proto-Gothic genre and introducing a novel way of storytelling. Walpole integrated "old" theatrical aspects with 'new' realism found in 'modern' novels to craft what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). This genre often harks back to medieval Gothic theater, architecture, and customs. Even when The Castle of Otranto was released, "gothic" described a range of people, styles, and eras, often seen as outdated compared to "modern" societal and literary progressions. The Gothic's blend of theatrical elements and the novel's new ability to delve into characters' psyches is what has allowed Gothic literature to endure, appearing both outdated and fresh to readers far removed from its original context.

A key theme in Gothic novels is Chivalry. The medieval concept of chivalry, or the training of an ideal knight, is both preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. For Gothic writers, chivalry symbolized the noble, honorable, and skilled knight—qualities they felt were lacking in society, especially Walpole. By romanticizing the "gothic past" through chivalric ideals, a bridge to Romanticism is suggested, with an aim to better the present. When Walpole penned The Castle of Otranto, he was amidst political turmoil and concerned about the future. Involved in politics and possibly facing unjust accusations, he may have believed that the moral integrity seen in the Gothic era was missing from contemporary society. This idea is evident in several characters, including Frederic. Before encountering Frederic, readers learn he represents many chivalric qualities. He is portrayed as:

Frederic is painted with numerous classic chivalric images; first and foremost, he is a prince who has endured hardships, been profoundly affected by tragedy, and is thought to have been slain by infidels. The "gallant and courteous Knight" character is exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management encompasses the series of activities involved in moving goods from the initial customer order through stages such as raw materials, supply, production, and finally to product distribution. The concept of supply chain management was coined by consultant Keith Oliver in 1982. He articulated the comprehensive process of planning, executing, and regulating the supply chain to effectively meet customer demands. This process hinges on six critical elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers employ these elements to ensure optimal customer service.

The supply chain process begins with production, serving as its cornerstone. This phase determines the timing, rationale, location, and methodology for production. Managers must be attuned to customer preferences, which can be discerned by analyzing market trends—an invaluable indicator of consumer demand. Upon understanding market demands, managers decide which products to manufacture and in what quantities. It's then essential to choose an appropriate production facility that balances volume and quality, aligning with customer satisfaction goals. Once the production site is established, management shifts focus to scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. The meticulous planning of each detail in production is crucial to avoid significant time and financial losses. For instance, in my experience at Wal-Mart and Target, both retailers had systematic guidelines for every operational aspect, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments. Such structured processes help maintain clarity and efficiency.

The next integral component of supply chain management is supply. Supply involves making strategic decisions to define a facility's core capabilities and develop outsourcing partnerships. A company might operate several production divisions for a single product, each with unique equipment, staff, and expertise. Managers must determine which division is best suited for specific product processes. Additionally, they might consider outsourcing to other companies to enhance velocity, which is the capacity to deliver quality and adaptability while minimizing or maintaining costs.

Victorian novels are renowned for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the period's aristocracy. However, two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are often regarded as Victorian yet deviate from this norm. These works incorporate elements of mystery and an unusual flair that are not typical of the era's novels. This approach enhances the depth of the characters, offering insights into their motivations and emotions.

"And now, a multitude of bewildering and confusing thoughts flooded his mind. It seemed as if he were still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were engaged in a heated argument: for the very words they spoke echoed in his ears; and when he focused his attention, ... he realized he was speaking to them.... Suddenly, he was startled by the sound of gunfire; loud cries and shouts filled the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and all was chaos and commotion, as some invisible force hurriedly whisked him away. Through all these rapid visions, there persisted a vague, uneasy awareness of pain, which wearied and tormented him endlessly." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels frequently employ mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the details and purposes differ in each instance. In Oliver Twist, these peculiar events often reveal insights into Oliver's inner struggles, his sources of pain, and his understanding of the true nature of the circumstances around him. When the incident of Oliver being shot is revisited in chapter 28, he relives the event vividly, as if in a dream, while he seeks help. The passage highlights the lack of control Oliver had over the unfolding events, as well as the severe state of his health, which is vividly depicted through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, numbing his senses to the point where he is unaware of the "unseen hand" carrying him away; he experiences his despair anew, detached from the initial shock of pain, as the pain is now an enduring presence linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises regarding whose intentions led to his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own. This shooting underscores the idea that Oliver has little control over anything, unable even to attempt to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is at risk. This passage also suggests a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as though old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair and affecting his ability to respond. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for the sake of preserving his own life.

"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it disappeared as soon as it arrived – and night descended once more; a night so long, yet so brief; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years back, I took on a role in an after-school program, where I tutored young students at the elementary level. My goal was to assist them in subjects where they faced challenges, though I was particularly strong in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to work with a boy named Adrian, who I recall was in the third or fourth grade, because he was having significant reading difficulties. It soon became apparent that his issues were unusual; while he could pronounce some letters flawlessly, others were a complete miss. It was quite strange. Although Adrian was of Latino descent, he spoke perfect English, which initially puzzled me. Our progress was slow until I met his mother one day. While babysitting a handful of students who hadn't gone on a field trip, Adrian's mother arrived. She couldn't speak English, only Spanish. With my limited Spanish skills—I was still learning—we managed to communicate. At that moment, it struck me: Adrian's reading issues weren't due to a disability; he simply wasn't familiar with the English alphabet. I can't say for sure if this realization made a significant difference for him, but I sincerely hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, particularly in California. It's a reminder that these barriers aren't always as apparent as one might assume. Even for a child fluent in spoken English, reading can present a major hurdle. I believe we can all acknowledge this problem, but the question is, how do we address it? In Adrian's situation, the solution was straightforward: focused tutoring in English reading, especially on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who have limited English proficiency, the solution is far more intricate. There's no single answer. A combination of dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, and ESL classes is necessary to tackle this issue effectively.

The dual language system, in particular, is a valuable approach—not only for children whose first language is Spanish but for all students. Research shows that students in two-way bilingual programs often surpass their peers academically. Despite concerns that such programs might be resource-intensive and not beneficial for the majority, this isn't true. If we implement these programs widely in classrooms, rather than treating them as exceptions, all students stand to gain. But how do we implement this? Requiring all teachers to be bilingual is impractical. Instead, it's feasible to have bilingual aides, tutors, or whatever title is suitable, to support this initiative.

From a young age, we're often introduced to the idea that something greater than ourselves exists, beyond our understanding. Some of us attend Sunday school to explore this concept, while others might go to Temple or search internally for answers. Many easily embrace the religious beliefs passed down by their parents. However, some of us outright reject these ideas, refusing to accept anything beyond our self-centered worlds. It's possible to adopt a belief system only to later shift to another. No matter the path, we strive to define ourselves through our personal views on spirituality. We seek guidance, hoping to move from darkness into light.

When I asked my father about his favorite bird, he replied, "A cardinal." We were on our porch, listening to rain drum on the tin roof while sharing cigarettes. The gutters channeled the rain, flooding the plants around the porch. My father gazed into the rain, with a look that seemed both introspective and reminiscent. Over recent months, he had grown thinner, his clothes hanging loosely, and his hair thinning more than I recalled. He continued staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt isolated and scared, unable to express how much I'd miss him, fearing that acknowledging it would make it more real. I hugged him, then sat closer, joining him in watching the June twilight rain.

That December, just five days after my twenty-second birthday, my father passed away. The treatments had not alleviated his pain but had extended his life a few months beyond doctors' predictions. I couldn't determine the value in prolonging his suffering. I questioned what kind of God would allow this. Alone at night, I offered no prayers, convinced that if God existed, He had long stopped listening to me.

I hadn't wanted to witness his transition from this life to another, so I didn't. I couldn't bear to watch the end of the life that brought me into this world. I chose to remember my father by his life, not his death. I understood him more than others, even his family, and knew he wouldn't want me, his only child, to witness his passing. I isolated myself in my room for three days, awaiting the inevitable news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an influential early advocate for Republicanism. Primarily an agriculturalist, his career in farming, coupled with a brief stint in politics, shaped his reputation for being vocal and committed to issues of personal liberty and governance. His belief in an agrarian society was central to his views on government. Taylor's efforts to preserve and promote what he deemed the most noble profession influenced his perspectives on sovereignty, the Constitution, and even the judicial system.

Taylor believed the United States had a unique chance to build an exemplary system, unencumbered by native traditions that might restrict the formation of self-governance. He was a fervent supporter of the natural rights of man, asserting that these rights are interconnected; the denial of one undermines them all, diminishing their collective value. Therefore, these rights should be beyond governmental reach. He argued that the so-called "state of nature" favored those with physical strength and cunning, but that this should not be the case within a civilized society.

To establish this ideal society, Taylor argued that government must recognize both the good and evil inherent in humanity. He was steadfast in his belief in a dualistic morality, asserting that "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He identified good principles as those safeguarding private property, enhancing agriculture, and discouraging capitalism. Taylor believed that a government founded on sound principles would function justly, despite being led by individuals driven by greed and self-interest. He saw self-interest as humanity's motivating force, deeming it harmful only when it led to the formation of sub-societies that thrived at the expense of others. A sound government was essential to curb man's natural flaws, requiring vigilant monitoring to prevent the introduction of detrimental principles.

Like many staunch Republicans of his era, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He supported a highly limited Federal government, restricted to powers explicitly granted by the Constitution. Aware that an expansive Federal government would be costly and potentially tyrannical, he also recognized the dangers of a simplistic, literal interpretation, which could become corrupt without considering the framers' intentions. Furthermore, Taylor viewed the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, as it more clearly defined the country as a collection of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

I gazed downward, my mind processing the scene in front of me without any particular emotion or connection. With a detached focus, I observed what lay before me, allowing thoughts to drift in and out of my consciousness almost as quickly as they appeared. It felt as though my mind was engaged in a fluid experience, absorbing the visuals without forming distinct, personal thoughts.

Inspired by an artist I once collaborated with, I invested in an art instruction book titled The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. Ever since childhood, I had harbored a desire to draw, and this book offered insights ranging from the basics of using a pencil to the cognitive processes involved in interpreting lines. One of its techniques involved framing a picture with a square to simplify complex scenes, such as a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen adjoining a dining room, into a more manageable image.

In that moment, as I looked down at the bowl before me, I found myself unable to apply that artistic frame mentally. Overwhelmed by the sight, I stood there in amazement. Just as Picasso explored his blue period and Monet had a penchant for greenery, I faced the origins of my own artistic journey, which I whimsically dubbed Work in Brown.

With my fingertips on the chosen tool, I felt muscles tense and relax as my hand moved purposefully, driven by creative intent. Water flowed smoothly, carrying away fragments to oblivion. My hand struck the toilet handle repeatedly, yet the stubborn brown package remained, clinging to the bottom like an unwelcome guest.

Holding a mop loosely, standing with feet apart, and a green tie uncomfortably tight around my neck, I regarded the unpleasant bundle left behind in the Rite Aid restroom. After several more flushes and moments of quiet reflection, I reached for the toilet paper, wrapping my hand until it resembled an oven mitt. Straightening up, then bending over, my hand slowly descended into the bowl, reminiscent of a mother retrieving a Thanksgiving turkey from the oven.

Young drivers face a significant risk on the roads, with multiple elements contributing to the high accident rates among teenagers in America. According to the National Institutes of Health, a major issue is that the adolescent brain is not fully developed to deal with the complexities of driving. In addition to this, the lack of driving experience among teens leads to more fatal accidents, an increased likelihood of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and veering off the road.  

Moreover, teenagers are particularly vulnerable when they drive with friends—a common scenario. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center found a link between the age of passengers and the frequency of traffic accidents. In response, California and other states have implemented temporary provisional licenses, which limit the hours teens can drive and restrict them from carrying other minors as passengers. 

However, I view these provisional licenses as temporary fixes. The core problem lies in the fact that, statistically, the youngest drivers are not equipped to manage the responsibilities and dangers of driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman argues that even 18 is too young for a standard driver’s license. According to USA Today, Zuckerman's research indicates that individuals under 19-20 years old often engage in risky behavior for excitement. It seems prudent to delay driving until this risk-taking behavior diminishes. If young teens continue to be licensed, we will see a rise in fatal accidents, with potentially alarming consequences in the coming years. By 2010, many children of the Baby Boomer generation will reach driving age, adding millions of new teen drivers to the roads.  

Addressing this issue through legislation could be straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver's education to prepare future drivers, but no one under 18 should drive. A provisional permit could still precede a full license, with a requisite number of driving hours, similar to current state requirements—such as California’s mandate of 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult. Given that teen driving statistics are concerning nationwide, a uniform national law could effectively safeguard teenagers across the country. The legislative solution I propose is not an unprecedented concept.

This essay addresses three key aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, a concise definition of the disorder is given. Then, the process of diagnosis is discussed, highlighting typical signs or "red flags." The essay concludes by suggesting ways a teacher in a mainstream classroom can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder, also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), pertains to how well the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. It specifically refers to the perceptual handling of auditory data in the CNS and the neurobiological activity that underpins this processing, generating electrophysiologic auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Essentially, it is a condition where the brain struggles to process what is heard. Individuals with CAPD can hear normally and are not classified as "hearing impaired"; the challenge lies in the brain’s ability to interpret sounds, such as distinguishing words or filtering conversations from background noise.

The earliest reference to what is now known as CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, initially termed "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), when researchers were studying children with communication disorders. In 1954, the Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing evaluations for these children. By 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and created a model to explain the physiology of the central auditory nervous system related to dichotic perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 further encouraged research on children with CAPD.

CAPD presents itself in various forms: affected individuals might struggle to pinpoint or hear sounds in space, have trouble distinguishing between multiple "acoustic events," fail to recognize sound patterns, or find it difficult to detect changes in speech, such as sarcasm. Sounds might be masked by subsequent noises, they may lack the ability to synthesize auditory clues into meaningful information, and they may not accurately perceive the sequence of auditory information (Ferre).

Diagnosing CAPD involves screening the patient through "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," performed by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others using diverse measures to assess auditory-related skills (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This process may include questionnaires, observational assessments of auditory responses, and interactions with specific stimuli. Currently, there is no single, consistently effective diagnostic tool or known cause for the disorder. Many tests present multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli, asking patients to differentiate among items like words or numbers. Advanced evaluations involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the corresponding responses.

I am committed to studying social work with the aim of building a career with the Division of Family and Children Services, where I hope to assist children facing abuse or neglect and lend support to families in distress. The values I bring to this field include service, respect, ethics, a dedication to fostering better relationships, and a personal commitment to ongoing professional development to ensure competence. These principles hold great significance not only within social work but also resonate deeply with me on a personal level.

From a young age, I've felt a strong desire to help others, though I wasn't always sure which career would allow me to do so. During my time in high school and college, I observed many people avoiding their problems or resorting to ineffective coping strategies. These observations led me to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Despite this, I remained uncertain about my career direction after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, so I took some time off. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy on her couch. She explained his situation: he was seeking refuge from abusive parents. The next day, he called the police to his home. Wanting to help, I went to his parents' house and shared my concerns with the police, mentioning my recent degree in Psychology. Since legal action wasn't an option, the police asked me to speak with the parents. They seemed anxious and provided excuses, labeling their son’s actions to involve outsiders as “manipulative” responses to minor family conflicts. This encounter pushed me to seriously consider a career in social work, focusing on helping children navigate family issues.

Social justice is another core value essential to social work. Society often emphasizes the importance of the individual and laments those who are lost, yet the societal notion of individuality often clings to outdated traditions rather than embracing true uniqueness. If society grieves for lost individuals, why do we strive for conformity? I value my individuality and resist conforming to societal norms. During my high school and college years, I stood against social injustice in various ways: expressing myself through unique hair colors, wearing clothes that reflected my personality, getting non-traditional ear piercings, joining the GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and actively opposing racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. Upholding social justice is a belief I am passionate about, and I remain committed to challenging social injustice.

This essay explores the Biological and Sociocultural frameworks as they pertain to insomnia, a sleep disorder. The biological perspective emphasizes inherited genetic traits and medical health factors. In contrast, the Sociocultural perspective examines how environmental interactions relate to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic conditions. This analysis of insomnia delves into these models, discussing selected research that helps clarify and expand upon each framework. The research findings are then assessed to highlight their individual strengths and limitations.

Sleep disorders can be categorized as primary sleep disorders, those related to other mental disorders, or those associated with other factors. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while those linked to other mental disorders are connected to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Additional sleep disorder categories may stem from medical issues or substance use. Dyssomnias encompass Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves difficulty in falling or staying asleep, whereas Primary Hypersomnia is characterized by trouble staying awake, both persisting for at least a month. Narcolepsy features symptoms like cataplexy and automatic REM. While Dyssomnias focus on sleep initiation and maintenance, Parasomnias are linked to behavioral or physiological irregularities during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders associated with other mental disorders involve sleep challenges due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Intellectual Disabilities). This review emphasizes insomnia and, to some extent, primary sleep disorders in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological perspective on sleep disorders considers genetic, hereditary, and physiological elements. Neurons in the hypothalamus that contain orexin play a crucial role in regulating sleep and wake states. A study involving mice demonstrated that phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons are specifically involved in sleep/wake regulation. Activation of the GABAA receptor triggers sleep-promoting responses, and its inhibition can lead to reduced anxiety and enhanced sleep. The GABAB agonist baclofen was found to increase sleep duration (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that results from animal models can be applicable to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. Issues or lack of this receptor could affect one's ability to sleep adequately without medication. The sociocultural implication is that if this phenotype is inherited, receptor changes could naturally disrupt an individual's sleep, adversely affecting areas like education, career, and routine activities requiring sustained attention.

I've been attending University Park for roughly two and a half years, which equates to about four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus can be challenging for many students, myself included. During my freshman year, I lived in a dorm in East Halls, which is nearly at the eastern edge of campus, aside from the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my residence in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building near the campus center could take up to 25 minutes, particularly when the weather was unfavorable, which is a frequent occurrence in State College. An alum who graduated not long before I did mentioned that East Halls dorms were once isolated by vast stretches of unused land. Nowadays, that space has been transformed into sports fields and large new buildings, such as the Creamery and a new health services facility, with apartments surrounding them. As campus continues to grow, moving from one place to another becomes increasingly challenging. What is the best solution for campus mobility? The answer lies in using bicycles. However, simply having bikes isn’t enough. Students need to utilize them, and the campus infrastructure must accommodate cyclists.

A friend of mine, who recently started cycling again after a break of several years, shared his thoughts. He questioned why he ever gave it up. "Bikes are fantastic," he remarked, "although it wasn't trendy to ride one for a while, it's really the best way to get around." Besides being healthy, cycling is the most efficient travel method. With a bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort, you can cover 30 miles or more. Like many students, I currently live off-campus, which is as far from the campus center as some dorms. Purchasing a bicycle has been my smartest choice this year. Each day, I have a class in the Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my place. Cycling can reduce that time to just 5 minutes if I ride swiftly. The only challenge is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas building from my house, and it can be a difficult road to navigate, whether on bike or on foot. While there are benefits to walking, my schedule is too packed to allow for it. Without my bike, walking would be my only dependable way to reach class. Walking to Thomas daily would consume an extra 30-40 minutes of my time. That adds up to over two and a half hours weekly. Plus, there’s the additional time I'd spend walking to and from other classes and appointments. That's more time than I can afford to lose.

In his novel Brave New World, Aldous Huxley presents a dystopian future where technology and capitalism pose significant threats. The society depicted prioritizes the community over the individual, with citizens trained from birth to seek immediate happiness. People in this world are mere players in a grander scheme, bound by a single ideology established by the World Controller. Through a Marxist perspective, one can see Huxley's skepticism about the evolving economic systems of his era. Terms frequently used in Marxist theory, such as hegemony and reification, underscore the idea that Huxley's novel critiques emerging economic systems from his time.

Capitalism is mocked through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. Essentially, ordinary people are unaware of their true economic relationships with other classes, as they focus on personal gain. This is attributed to the ideological control over the proletariat and common workers, which is evident in the conditioning witnessed in Brave New World. The lower classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, lack true autonomy; through hypnopædia, their desire to consume and spend is prioritized above all. This is controlled by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that social classes are completely dominated by a separate group, is evident here. The lower classes are oblivious to their manipulation, quite literally buying into an ideology that supports capitalism and consumerism. The upper classes are aware but largely passive, with few exceptions like Bernard. The interactions between social classes highlight the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In Brave New World, meaningful relationships between individuals are absent. Major characters lack depth, suggesting that technology and capitalism together strip individuals of free will and self-expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent, with interactions kept superficial. This is illustrated by men's comments about women focusing on their physical traits and women's open discussions about their encounters. Furthermore, the complacency of each social class with their hierarchical status reflects the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their complete obedience to their societal roles aligns with Marxist views on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform to their peers.

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in an Islam course at CBC. A central topic of lively debate in the class was the question of whether Islam is a hostile religion. I find this question increasingly pertinent today. Reflecting on the events following 9/11, I've noticed a shift in the mass media's portrayal of Islam and extremists—from a hostile perspective to a more tolerant stance in America. Back in 2001, it seemed unlikely that a presidential candidate with a name like Borac Obama, hinting at a Muslim heritage, could have emerged.

The Prophet's biography captivates me because it seems to contradict Muhammad's historical persona as I understood it. Previously, I was under the impression that Muhammad coerced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and compelling them to adopt the religion. However, the biography portrays him as a misunderstood martyr, who humbly engaged with others, leading people to recognize the 'truth' of his teachings and seek him out.

Additionally, there are striking parallels between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' attributed to Muhammad. A notable example is the episode where Muhammad supposedly multiplied mutton and milk to satisfy forty men. This narrative style suggests the writers sought to present Muhammad as a humble prophet, whose life was defined by truth and miracles, rather than needing validation. I find this portrayal problematic as it seems to undermine Jesus Christ's life and miracles, almost as if credit is being shifted from Jesus to Muhammad.

The biography also contains numerous anecdotes that appear to aim at demonstrating 'witness' or independent conversions to Islam. However, many of these stories are relayed from third-party perspectives, like a chain of hearsay. While intended to substantiate the authenticity of these accounts, I feel it instead casts doubt and makes the stories appear more questionable.

What troubles me most about this work is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a divine figure—humble, wise, and gentle. Yet, historical accounts challenge the notion of Muhammad as a gentle and humble leader. I wonder if contemporary Muslims are aware of the true historical context of Muhammad's ascent to power.

The original teachings and beliefs of Jesus during his life quickly became overshadowed as Christian thought evolved after his time. Observing this history broadly reveals a pattern of Christianity drifting further from its roots. In today's world, we see an increasing awareness and an unprecedented push towards progressive thinking. While traditionalists persist and resist new ideas beyond their familiar teachings, they may not hold enough sway to shape the entire population. Among Christians, historical consciousness is expected to grow significantly in the coming years. There will be a widespread desire to separate doctrines that were later added to Christianity from the original intentions of its founder. This process might take decades or even centuries, but it is seen as unavoidable: a significant shift in Christian history will occur, steering it back toward its foundational form. A movement will gain momentum, peeling away layers of added doctrine as if time were reversing, until what remains is the essence of what Jesus shared with humanity, before others claimed similar revelations. As this movement spreads across the United States and Europe, drawing people to worship as though they were contemporaries of Jesus, adhering solely to his teachings, the church as an institution will continue to guide the process. However, with this regression of theological development, the vast diversity within Christianity will gradually diminish, leading to more uniformity in beliefs and practices. Instead of highlighting differences across regions, denominations, and various divisions, growing similarities will emerge. Human history includes many examples of significant reversions. For instance, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, which later embraced Christianity. Our nation has shifted from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The forthcoming major reversion will unfold within the Christian religion, seeking its origins and reducing its diversity. This transformation will be facilitated by interpreting Jesus' words as metaphorical rather than literal. So, what transpired since Jesus' lifetime? Looking back, we see Judaism as the theological foundation of Christianity. By the time Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the concept of a divinely revealed faith, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion. However, the Jewish population was not unified; they were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of ordinary people.

In my view, "The Jungle" illustrates the inherent tendency of humans to be greedy and self-serving. People are primarily concerned with improving their own circumstances without considering those less fortunate. This theme is exemplified throughout "The Jungle," particularly in the portrayal of factory owners and managers. Their sole focus is on expanding and enhancing their enterprises, showing little to no concern for the consequences of their actions on others. Upton Sinclair's narrative conveys this indifference vividly: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair emphasizes the environmental devastation caused by pollution, highlighting the disregard owners have for the welfare of people and animals affected by it. They ignore the harmful smoke emissions and the animal waste runoff from the numerous pens in Packingtown.

The disregard extends to their workforce, whom they exploit to amass wealth. Their priority is maximizing profits, as depicted by Sinclair's observation: "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." Workers endure grueling hours only to be abruptly laid off, often without notice or severance. During the period depicted in "The Jungle," labor laws safeguarding workers' rights were scarce, allowing management to impose harsh working conditions. Although the narrative does not explicitly state it, the residents of Packingtown were expected to endure these dire circumstances at work and in their communities. There were no supportive agencies or resources for laborers. Unions existed but frequently exploited workers, profiting from their plight. The workers, trapped in a system akin to slavery, had no escape: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Edgar Allan Poe considered "Dream-Land" to be among his finer poetic works. Within this poem, he employs the term "Thulé" in both lines 6 and 56, a reference that Mabbott links back to Virgil. In classical literature, Virgil used "Thulé" to describe an island situated to the north of Britain, regarded by the Greeks as the boundary of the known world. While Virgil indeed used this term, there exists a more contemporary source that deserves acknowledgment. Poe had a keen interest in German authors, which is significant in understanding his influences.

The importance of this reference lies in demonstrating Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt, in his work "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," observes parallels between their poems, suggesting that Poe was drawing inspiration from Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature highlights Goethe as a renowned author of the poetic drama "Faust," released in two parts, with the first in 1808 and the second coinciding with Goethe's death in 1832. Within the second part of "Faust" is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé," which tells the story of a king who becomes despondent after his wife's passing, leading to heavy drinking and sorrow. Eventually, the king decides to die, bequeathing his possessions to his children except for a goblet, which he throws into the sea before closing his eyes and dying. The portrayal of the King of Thulé bears a striking resemblance to the king in "Dream-Land," possibly reflecting Poe’s own experiences with loss and alcohol. Notably, "Faust" was adapted into a romantic drama by H. P. Grattan in 1842, shortly before Poe's use of "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe's writings contain two references to Thule. He mentions "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum" and uses this phrase twice in "Dream-Land," effectively framing the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be viewed as complementary works. In "Dream-Land," the narrator describes a Thule landscape as dark, desolate, haunted by departed friends, and devoid of color. These elements resonate with "The King of Thule," where the king mourns his wife, feels isolated, and loses his desire to govern or live. The entirety of "Dream-Land" reads as if the narrator has stepped into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a pivotal literary figure Poe would have been acquainted with, if only due to his respect for Tennyson. Poe expressed his admiration for Tennyson, which suggests an exposure to Goethe’s works through the numerous versions produced following the original publication.

In the context of California law, can a customer injured by slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be granted punitive damages if it's shown that the store manager acted with malice, having been informed twice about the spill and neglecting to address it for half an hour while having dinner? 

It's unlikely that a judge will outright dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify such an award, the plaintiff needs to demonstrate that the defendant's behavior was willfully and consciously indifferent to the likely harm it would cause, alongside proving the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have foreseen the potential harm from ignoring a spill, given that multiple customers at D&D had suffered injuries from slipping incidents in the months leading up to her accident. Despite this awareness, he failed to address the spill. Although the argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less compelling, it remains plausible considering that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009, yet Martin did not take adequate steps to ensure the store's safety.

On the evening of October 13, 2009, at 5:00 p.m., Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin replied that he was on a dinner break and “didn’t have time to deal with customer complaints.” Another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill to Martin at 5:15 p.m., receiving the same response. By 5:30 p.m., Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill, suffering a serious back injury. Before Palmer's fall, five slip-and-fall incidents had already been reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is pursuing compensatory and punitive damages for her injury, and the decision at hand is whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff may be awarded punitive damages for breaching a non-contractual obligation if the defendant acted with “oppression, fraud, or malice” as per Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The law defines malice as behavior intended to cause harm, or if not intentional, behavior that is “despicable” and executed with “a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others,” id. at § (c)(1). Courts have deemed conduct malicious when done with conscious disregard for the plaintiff’s rights, particularly when the defendant “was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences.” Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

From a young age, she felt like something crucial was missing in her life. This yearning was persistent and unfulfilled, beginning around the age of 14 when she was navigating the early stages of adolescence. Even by 17, the feeling lingered. Over time, she realized it was not a thing she sought but a connection with someone. However, no boys caught her interest, despite several attempting to win her over in their awkward ways. She often pondered this peculiar situation, trying to understand why a teenage girl like herself felt this way. Years of reflection provided various theories, yet none seemed convincing enough. Thus, she continued her journey, always questioning her desires.

Life at home was typically serene. Her parents were peaceful individuals, rarely arguing with each other or with her, except when it came to her asserting her independence. She was the lively counterpart to her calm parents, her vibrant and engaging personality making her well-liked.

Yet today was far from calm. As she moved through the house, searching for fresh inspiration, a sudden scream from the kitchen pierced the air, her mother's voice. Panic set in as she rushed to the kitchen, calling out, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother lay on the floor, wincing in pain and repeating "Ow" with labored breaths. Instinctively, she rushed to help, placing a hand on her mother. "Ouch ... sweetie, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital," her mother managed to say, her voice strained. Recognizing her mother's distress, she asked where to lift her, grateful for her strength-training classes. Gently, she carried her mother to the car, settled her in the back, and drove to the hospital.

The hospital was filled with the sterile scent of disinfectant and an undercurrent of anxiety. But she was too focused on her mother to notice. Swiftly, she carried her mother inside, calling for medical assistance. Medical staff quickly surrounded them, placing her mother on a gurney and whisking her away for immediate attention, leaving her daughter to wait and worry.

Her mother had taken a fall from a stepping stool while reaching for a vase on the top shelf of their cabinet.

The purpose of this research was to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and death from stroke. The aMed diet is a variation of the traditional Med diet, emphasizing greater intake of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (as opposed to saturated fats), and fish, while reducing the consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Earlier prospective studies have shown an inverse relationship between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of total mortality and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, with one intervention trial indicating that the Med diet is more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the ratio of total cholesterol to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in individuals with obesity. However, previous studies did not concentrate on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are part of the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Between 1984 and 2004, the researchers calculated an aMed diet score six times based on self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of the nurses remained involved throughout the 20-year duration. Validation studies were conducted on the FFQs. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through the review of medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, incidents were labeled "probable" and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified this way. Factors such as body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was evaluated.

To minimize random variations for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated by averaging scores from the previous two years. Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could introduce bias in results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was employed to examine the relationship between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was correlated with a decreased risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over the 20 years of follow-up, there were 2,391 new cases of CHD, 1,763 new cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combining fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

A sign claims Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, known for her role in the film Juno, stands by herself at a street corner, holding a piece of cardboard above her head with the startling message scrawled on it in Sharpie. Burma, which is also called Myanmar, is located in Southeast Asia and has been under the control of a harsh military junta since they seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, the country experienced its first significant public protests in a decade, spearheaded by a large group of Burmese monks. These demonstrations became known as "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. Initially, the general public began to support the movement, and the government reluctantly permitted peaceful gatherings. However, the situation escalated into severe violence, with the military openly attacking and looting monasteries. Foreign journalists were detained, and Kenji Nagai, a Japanese photojournalist, was killed during a protest on September 27, 2007. While official reports state 13 fatalities, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army shortly before the official report, claimed, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

These events are not isolated in history. The suppression of dissent by governments to maintain control has been a recurring theme throughout civilization. Roman emperors once declared divine authority over their societies. Japanese emperors were believed to be gods themselves, leading their people toward technological and cultural advancements. Meanwhile, in modern times, George W. Bush, the U.S. president at the time, held weekly discussions with Ted Haggard, leader of the group Stupid People Worldwide, an offshoot of the Republic Party.

Notable historical parallels include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to oppose government authoritarianism. The death toll from that event varies, with Chinese government figures citing 200-300 deaths, while the Chinese Red Cross reported between 2,000-3,000 fatalities. Additionally, the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s saw Hutu militias, with government support, systematically killing Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnicity. Hitler’s 'Third Reich,' during which Jewish individuals were systematically exterminated across several countries, stands as another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's influence on jazz can be largely attributed to his enduring career and his remarkable talent in shaping his orchestra. While Ellington's piano presence may be subtle in many of the pieces chosen for this assignment, his brilliance as a composer lies in his ability to craft intricate compositions that highlight the unique talents of his band members. He designed frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while also composing tightly orchestrated sections that drew on the distinctive styles of his musicians to emphasize musical concepts. This approach allowed him to focus on the overall tone of the orchestra, generating cohesive and innovative sounds for each piece. Ellington's deep understanding of each musician's sound and their role within the ensemble enabled him to create some of the most groundbreaking and ingenious works in the history of jazz.

In discussing Ellington's innovative sound, the Grove Music dictionary highlights "Creole Love Call," an example of his use of voice "as a jazz instrument" without the limitations of lyrics. This piece illustrates Ellington's skill in enhancing the style of his soloists, a quality evident throughout his career. The piece is a slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues composition with six choruses:

1. A call and response between voice and reeds, beginning with a smooth, melodic voice that becomes rougher towards the end.
2. A muted trumpet solo that expands on the basic melody, emphasizing extended blue notes.
3. A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
4. The full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
5. The climactic chorus, where the reeds initiate the call and response in a high register, supported by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
6. A return to the original structure with a call and response between voice and reeds, featuring the voice utilizing the "growl" technique as an instrument.

A brief tag concludes the piece with a vocal run and a dissonant trombone ending. Ellington's use of voice to add tonal color to this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait prevalent in his work.

In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington merges his expertise in orchestration with his keen sense of tonal color. A call and response sequence between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing merges the vocal quality of Miley's trumpet and the instrumental quality of Cox's voice to create a rich, complementing sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" further develops these ideas, as Ellington skillfully employs Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a cornerstone of Ellington’s orchestra, to introduce the melody on muted trombone with great effect.

What drives the evolutionary patterns we observe in living organisms? Are there particular limitations or factors that shape how these changes occur over time? Back in 1917, D’Arcy Thompson remarked that defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical terms was a task barely begun by zoologists, and this challenge remains today. In recent years, mathematical modeling has been utilized to study the general process of mollusk shell formation across both individual development and evolutionary history, as demonstrated in works like those by Raup and Stanley in 1981. Our research is investigating the use of mathematical modeling on the developmental and evolutionary changes in the Prunum species. By integrating these models with experimental studies, we aim to uncover the mechanisms that guide the extent and direction of evolutionary changes. We employed X-ray images of Prunum species to extract quantitative parameters, which were then used to simulate both potential and actual shell structures. These parameters were input into the CerioShell software program developed by Stone in 1995. Our models of hypothetical shell forms help us understand the limits of morphological changes in Prunum. These findings are being combined with experimental and descriptive research to enhance our comprehension of large-scale evolutionary events within this group.

A shell can be conceptualized as a tubular structure that progresses through time, completing rotations in 360-degree space. The rotations of a coiled shell are termed whorls, spiraling around an imagined central axis, known as the columella, which runs through the core of the shell. The rate at which whorls expand differs, and a continuous line called a suture delineates each whorl. Typically, the largest whorl is the final one, referred to as the body whorl. All preceding whorls form the spire. The spire's tip is the apex, while the base is found at the opposite end. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening known as the aperture.

Shells can be observed from various perspectives, including apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. Traditionally, the apertural view is most common, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex directed upwards.

A technique for counting whorls involves viewing the shell from the apex and identifying the start of the first suture. A line is drawn to split the shell into two sections, and whorls are counted from this line, estimated to the nearest quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be visualized as a succession of apertures moving through time and space as the organism builds its shell. One can trace the path of the aperture using the coordinates of the center and the horizontal and vertical radii of each whorl's aperture.

This path can be depicted graphically and mathematically. With a mathematical model in place, it becomes feasible to adjust parameters and alter the mollusk’s shell formation process.

Over the past decade, Indonesia's neonatal and infant mortality rates have shown little change. Despite progress toward achieving many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation improvements, the advancements in child and maternal health fall significantly short of the targets set for 2015. This analysis will explore the various causes of these deficiencies and emphasize the importance of reinforcing the health system over implementing isolated program interventions.

Indonesia has seen progress in the percentage of births attended by skilled health workers, now at 72%. However, this statistic includes traditional practitioners like midwives, who lack the ability to perform medical interventions in complicated pregnancies, which contributes to high maternal mortality rates due to hemorrhage. Thus, the perceived progress in this area is somewhat deceptive, indicating much more work is needed. Moreover, there has been a reduction in the proportion of children under five with diarrhea receiving professional health treatment. Although data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is evident that this is another area of concern, with low coverage nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates are still below expected levels, around 4%, highlighting another issue. While urban areas have a 7% c-section rate, rural areas are at just 2%, indicating a disparity in healthcare coverage. Access to healthcare is concentrated in urban regions. Moreover, there is a 27% gap in service utilization between the wealthiest and poorest, showing that socioeconomic status significantly impacts healthcare access, likely because of out-of-pocket expenses.

When considering future strategies to improve neonatal and maternal health indicators, the primary question is how best to address service deficiencies. Should Indonesia focus on specific programmatic approaches or enhance the overall health system without targeting pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? Programmatic solutions are appealing due to their defined objectives and typically faster results. However, they have drawbacks, such as diverting resources from other health areas and concentrating human resources in more funded sectors, like the effect of international HIV/AIDS funding on family planning. Additionally, running multiple separate programs for a single area can lead to redundant services and lack of coordination, increasing the administrative burden for supplies and funding.

Over the last century, the classification of Popular Music has expanded to such an extent that it encompasses an overwhelming number of genres, making it challenging to catalog them all comprehensively. Adding to the complexity, nearly every genre—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—has given rise to numerous sub-genres and further sub-categories within their realms. Among these, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock stands out as one of the most varied and expressive branches of popular music over the past four decades. Its expressiveness is evident in its portrayal of a broad spectrum of emotions, often skewing toward the darker hues. Diversity in Heavy Metal emerged rapidly as people recognized its adaptability, leading them to innovate their own sub-genres, which then evolved into sub-sub-genres, continuing this trend to the present day.

Currently, the heavy metal scene has fragmented into so many distinct niches that defining what constitutes heavy metal has become increasingly challenging. It has absorbed a multitude of influences from other genres, yet like all musical forms, it originated from a specific point. To truly grasp the metal music prevalent today, one must first comprehend the essence of the metal movement and why it transcends being merely a genre.

In several respects, metal is a movement characterized by its embrace of darkness. It can be described as music that embodies "more"—more bass, more volume, more aggression, and more theatrical elements. It shuns simplicity and highlights technical skill; musicians in metal bands are typically adept with their instruments, which is evident in their performances. Additionally, it may not come as a shock that metal is a movement significantly influenced by drug use. The psychedelic drug surge of the mid-1970s led to increasingly wild and surreal records, with drugs often serving as a catalyst for such creativity. Metal music carries many dark, visceral attributes, which were relatively novel in the music scene, as much of popular music had previously avoided delving into the darker emotional territories. Furthermore, later iterations of metal drew inspiration from the dark, visceral elements prevalent during the Romantic Era. The following lyrics exemplify the darkness integral to the movement:

These lines from "Helter Skelter" reveal the Beatles' darker side, reflecting a tumultuous journey, often attributed to drug influence. This song is regarded by some as one of the pioneering Heavy Metal tracks. It was crafted in response to a Rolling Stones song that also explored heavier, darker themes. The Beatles sought to demonstrate their capability to match the Stones' intensity, leading them to include the song on "The White Album."

Several decades prior to the emergence of Surrealist artists and their dream-inspired creations, Henri Rousseau was ingeniously sculpting his own dreams, both in a literal and metaphorical sense. "The Dream," a painting completed in 1910 by the renowned Post-Impressionist, not only illustrates a woman marveling at the wonders of a dreamland but also symbolizes Rousseau's personal ambitions and aspirations as an artist. From the onset of his career, he longed for recognition, acceptance, and acclaim from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, yet he encountered a significant internal conflict in his pursuit of these dreams. "The Dream" embodies Rousseau's lifelong internal battle: whether to adapt or emulate certain artistic styles to gain acceptance in the critical art world he cherished, or to remain creatively autonomous and distinct, forging his own path. 

To understand "The Dream" from this perspective, it is essential to be acquainted with Rousseau's life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwestern France, Rousseau was the son of a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed a comfortable middle-class life (Shattuck 47). He had no formal artistic education; instead, he worked for the French government as a gabelou, a municipal toll employee, until he was forty years old, acquiring the misleading nickname douanier, meaning customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The passing of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left him with only one surviving child, a daughter named Julia, and profound sorrow (Shattuck 49). Seeking solace and renewal, he turned to painting as a refuge. Unlike his contemporaries who often romanticized the peasantry in their art, Rousseau was fundamentally a folk artist with the hopes and aspirations typical of his social class.

Rousseau's fixation on gaining acceptance in the art community is understandable when considered in context: not only did he lack formal training and begin his artistic journey later in life, but he was also creating art alongside many other skilled and renowned modern artists. Despite years of effort, Rousseau did not receive significant recognition until around the same time that Matisse was establishing his own artistic reputation. In "Modern French Painters," Jan Gordon argues that although Rousseau and Matisse were technically rivals, they differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their motivations for creating art: "Matisse aimed to avoid painting in a clichéd manner, whereas Rousseau sought to create works so conventional that he would gain admission to the Artiste Français" (92).

Various eminent thinkers have often drawn parallels between ethics and aesthetics, suggesting a deep link between truth and beauty. I feel there is a foundational basis for this idea. In his poem "Ode on a Grecian Urn," John Keats famously states, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of our knowledge comes from formal education or personal experiences. Yet, our grasp of ethics and aesthetics seems, as Keats hints, to come naturally rather than through conventional teaching methods. Ethics and aesthetics are more about describing than prescribing. When we delve into morality and beauty, we're generally trying to understand why a particular artwork or piece of literature is considered beautiful, or why certain actions are deemed moral, instead of creating a rigid framework for evaluating art or ethical conduct.

Importantly, critiques of art or morality often fall short of fully encapsulating what makes something good or beautiful. For instance, discussions about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on elements like composition, contrast, or its cultural significance, but these do not entirely explain why it is revered as great art. Often, when someone is asked about a favorite piece of art or literature, they might start with, “There's just something about it,” before offering a more detailed analysis. I think that neither art nor morals can be wholly broken down into descriptions of their characteristics. As Flannery O'Connor notes, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how thoroughly we attempt to characterize a literary work, there remains an ineffable quality. Similarly, I believe ethics shares this feature. Wittgenstein expresses this by saying, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.” This ineffable "something," or je ne sais quoi, I propose, is the most compelling aspect of both art and morality, and this transcendental quality is what links ethics and aesthetics.

I think the closeness between morality and art stems from our profound experience of both on a level that is intuitive, to borrow from Kant's terminology. They affect us in a way that is felt deeply but not easily articulated. This connection is even more pronounced in the literary arts. As McKean points out, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Modern-day Germany stands as a robust and united nation, showcasing a diverse cultural heritage stretching from the alpine shadows of Munich to the Baltic coast of Kiel. This cultural tapestry extends from Cologne on the Rhine through Germany's heartland to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given this rich cultural amalgamation, it's no wonder that contemporary Germany has roots in numerous sources and tribes.

The ancestral homeland of the Germans, Germania, is steeped in mystery regarding the origin of its name, a topic of much debate among historians and scholars. Tacitus suggested the name originated from a Germanic tribe once known as the Tungrians, who had been referred to as Germans before they crossed the Rhine to confront the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first documented the term “Germanus” in his account of the Gallic Wars, distinguishing between the conquered Gauls and the Germanic tribes, who frequently crossed the Rhine under dubious pretenses. Caesar adopted this term from the Gauls themselves to differentiate the unconquered tribes. Some theories suggest the name signified a neighboring tribe in the Gaulish language. In the opening of his first book on the Gallic Wars, Caesar remarked: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC). Other interpretations link the name to the spear, or "ger," used in warfare (O.E.D, 2010), or possibly to the Old Irish word "garim," meaning “to shout,” hinting at the Germans’ loud or boisterous nature (Names of Germany).

Tacitus, an early Roman historian, penned "De Origine et situ Germanorum" in AD 98, exploring the origins of the Germans. He asserted that the Germans were likely indigenous, not intermingled with other races through immigration or contact. He wrote: “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?” (Tacitus, 98).

As for departing Rome for Germania, the Romans seldom did so. Instead, they ventured into Germania for trade and occasional military campaigns, yet typically returned to their expansive empire. As Germanic tribes emerged in the mid-first century, they inhabited the Roman Empire's frontiers, exchanging land-derived goods and military service within the Roman army (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17).

In Shakespeare's Twelfth Night, the play explores the notion that while disguises can be effective tools for deception over long periods, ultimately, one must discard these façades to avoid losing their true self. However, ceasing such deception can lead to feelings of alienation. Thus, an individual must choose between preserving their own identity and maintaining relationships with others. Some may react indifferently upon learning they were deceived, but others might not be as forgiving, feeling insulted by the entire ruse.

The issue of deception becomes particularly complex when it involves gender role reversal, raising significant questions, particularly: why? What drives a person to abandon their identity and adopt a disguise as the opposite gender? For Viola, it serves as a means of self-preservation: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249).

Viola, arriving in an unfamiliar place, chooses to disguise herself as a man to shield herself from potential threats. Although her plan is successful, it distances her from the women around her, depriving her of a vital support network. Complicating matters further, she is so adept at her disguise that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love with her: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Additionally, Viola must navigate her repressed romantic feelings for Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

To contemporary audiences, Twelfth Night might appear to illustrate how deception can reveal hidden emotions, especially for Olivia and Orsino. The text suggests that these characters might have latent desires that Viola/Cesario's presence compels them to confront. For instance, is Olivia drawn to Cesario merely because he seems to be a man, or does she have unspoken feelings for women? It seems unlikely, as Shakespeare’s portrayal of Olivia appears to satirize individuals of his era who judge others based solely on appearance.

This is further demonstrated by how easily Olivia transfers her romantic affections from Cesario to Sebastian, subsequently viewing Cesario/Viola as part of her family rather than a romantic partner: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

The harshness of German colonial rule has been highlighted by numerous commentators, particularly regarding the atrocities committed against the Ovaherero and Nama peoples in German South West Africa.
